  "slug": "chana-masala",
  "title": "Chana masala",
  "subtitle": "Spiced chickpea curry with tomato and garam masala",
  "excerpt": "Chickpeas simmered in a thick sauce of caramelised onion, ginger, garlic, tomato, and spices. A Punjabi curry-house staple and one of the most popular vegetarian dishes on the British Indian menu. The chickpeas are cooked until they absorb the sauce and the whole dish becomes deep and fragrant. Served with rice or bhatura (fried bread).",
  "type": "RECIPE",
  "sourceNotes": "Chana masala (chole masala) is a Punjabi dish eaten across Northern India and Pakistan, brought into the British curry-house tradition in the 1970s. It is documented in Madhur Jaffrey's cookbooks and is one of the most commonly ordered vegetarian dishes in British Indian restaurants.",
  "body": {
    "type": "doc",
    "content": [
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Tinned chickpeas work perfectly here and make this a very quick dish. The key step is mashing roughly 20% of the chickpeas once they're in the sauce, this thickens the curry and gives it a denser body that raw chickpeas don't provide. Press the back of the spoon against the chickpeas in the pan a few times rather than using a masher.",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "The spice blend for chana masala is heavier on cumin and coriander than a standard curry base, and dried mango powder (amchoor) gives the characteristic slight sourness. Without amchoor, a small squeeze of lemon juice at the end achieves a similar effect. Either approach works; the tanginess is the point.",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
