        },
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Method",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 3
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Build the base",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Heat the {{vegetable-oil}} in a wide pan over medium-high heat. Add the {{cumin-seeds}} and fry for 30 seconds until they pop. Add the {{onion}} and cook for 12 to 15 minutes until deep golden. Add the {{garlic}} and {{ginger-root}} and cook for 2 minutes. Add the {{cumin-ground}}, {{coriander-ground}}, {{chilli-powder}}, and {{turmeric}} and stir for 1 minute. Add the {{tinned-tomatoes}} and cook for 8 to 10 minutes until reduced to a thick paste.",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 3
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Add chickpeas and finish",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Add the {{chickpeas-tinned}} and 150 ml water. Stir well to coat in the sauce. Simmer over medium heat for 15 minutes. Using the back of a spoon, roughly crush about a quarter of the chickpeas against the side of the pan to thicken the sauce. Stir in the {{garam-masala}} and season with salt and a squeeze of lemon juice if using. The sauce should be thick and clinging to the chickpeas.",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "troubleshooter",
        "attrs": {
          "items": [
            {
              "fix": "Simmer uncovered and stir frequently. Crush more chickpeas against the pan to release their starch and thicken the sauce",
              "cause": "Not enough reduction before or after adding chickpeas",
              "symptom": "Sauce is too thin"
            },
            {
              "fix": "Taste after 15 minutes and adjust salt. The chickpeas need time to absorb the spiced sauce, don't rush this stage",
              "cause": "Under-seasoned or insufficient simmer time",
              "symptom": "Chickpeas taste bland"
            },
            {
              "fix": "Add lemon juice cautiously. It should brighten without dominating. If too sharp, add a pinch of sugar to balance",
              "cause": "Too much lemon juice added",
              "symptom": "Too sharp"
            },
            {
              "fix": "Reduce the heat to medium after adding chickpeas. Stir frequently and add a splash of water if sticking",
              "cause": "Heat too high after chickpeas added",
              "symptom": "Sauce sticking to the pan"
            }
          ]
        }
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Where this dish lives",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Chana masala is the most ordered vegetarian curry on the British Indian menu. It works as a main with rice or as a side with meat curries. In Punjab it is served with bhatura, a deep-fried leavened bread, as chole bhature. That pairing is popular for breakfast or lunch. The British curry-house version is drier and more tomato-forward than the Punjabi original, which can lean on tamarind and dried mango for its sour note.",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      }
    ]
